# Finance Ledger Reconciliation Automation

This is a finance ledger reconciliation automation project. It processes accounting
ledgers (organisation ledgers and party ledgers) and reconciles transactions between
the two sides.

The pipeline spans the full flow: raw PDF extraction -> deterministic formalization
(with optional, token-limited AI layout profiling / failed-row repair / unknown-label
grouping) -> deterministic-first reconciliation -> bounded AI arbitration for unresolved
clusters -> deterministic post-validation -> submission-quality workbook generation.

## Hard rules for AI / Cursor

- Deterministic matching always runs first and preserves strong matches.
- AI may make final reconciliation decisions only in the bounded AI reconciliation
  arbitration layer, only from supplied row evidence, only when deterministic matching
  cannot confidently resolve the case, and only after deterministic post-validation.
  Invalid or low-confidence AI decisions go to Review Queue.
- AI arbitration must use compact candidate packets, row IDs, centralized config caps,
  deterministic fingerprints, and cache reuse. Never send whole ledgers, PDFs, or sheets.
- Every AI decision must remain workbook-visible, traceable, auditable, and reversible.
- Raw extraction and formalization must preserve the original source text and page
  references. Never drop, rewrite, or "clean" source text during extraction.
- Do NOT invent or infer missing ledger fields. If a value is absent in the source, leave
  it absent (empty), never fabricate it.
- Do NOT overwrite, mutate, or delete source files (PDFs, workbooks, original uploads).
- Do NOT print, log, or dump secrets (e.g. `.env` contents, API keys).
- Do NOT send financial evidence to a hosted provider unless the existing explicit
  hosted-approval gate passes. Even when approved, send only minimal bounded packets.

## Engineering preferences

- Prefer small, single-purpose scripts.
- Use type hints on functions.
- Use `pathlib.Path` for filesystem paths (Windows-compatible).
- Raise clear, actionable errors that name the offending path or condition.
- Produce audit-friendly output: preserve raw rows, record page numbers, methods used,
  timestamps, and per-page status so results can be traced back to the source.
